snippet.textDisplay: I'd just like to say that no matter how much I love Star Wars, it's somewhat incorrect to say that they "pioneered" most of these special effects. Almost a decade earlier Stanley Kubrick had pioneered most of these things, especially the use of models, motion-controlled camera rigs, mattes, multiple exposures, etc. in order to create the FX for 2001: A Space Odyssey. And he did it better. To my eyes, the spaceship model effects work in 2001 is still almost flawless, where the original Star Wars FX shots show clear signs of matting and fringing, etc. Just thought I'd do a shout out for the master, Mr. Kubrick.
snippet.textOriginal: I'd just like to say that no matter how much I love Star Wars, it's somewhat incorrect to say that they "pioneered" most of these special effects. Almost a decade earlier Stanley Kubrick had pioneered most of these things, especially the use of models, motion-controlled camera rigs, mattes, multiple exposures, etc. in order to create the FX for 2001: A Space Odyssey. And he did it better. To my eyes, the spaceship model effects work in 2001 is still almost flawless, where the original Star Wars FX shots show clear signs of matting and fringing, etc. Just thought I'd do a shout out for the master, Mr. Kubrick.

snippet.textDisplay: What if they made a modern Star Wars film (or new sci fi action film) where they are only allowed to use these practical techniques? Maybe modern robotics tech for some of the pre-calculated model motion and maybe a computer for compositing to clean it up a bit better instead of the 'analog' blocking. And modern cameras for quality reasons are ok. But no cgi elements, no digital art. I'd love to see a Kick-starter or maybe a director's passion project as a short film in that style in modern day and try to make it as complex and good looking as possible.
snippet.textOriginal: What if they made a modern Star Wars film (or new sci fi action film) where they are only allowed to use these practical techniques? Maybe modern robotics tech for some of the pre-calculated model motion and maybe a computer for compositing to clean it up a bit better instead of the 'analog' blocking. And modern cameras for quality reasons are ok. But no cgi elements, no digital art. I'd love to see a Kick-starter or maybe a director's passion project as a short film in that style in modern day and try to make it as complex and good looking as possible.

snippet.textDisplay:
The name of the walking machines on Hoth are pronounced like the word “at” said twice; “at-at” or “at-ats”. Two words, each with a short “a”.
Not “A-T, A-T”. I cringed every time.
And Jedi is pronounced with a short “e” and a long “i”. Jed-eye. Not Jed-ee.
Other than that it was a great show.

Stumbled upon you guys, but one of the best films I saw as a kid and learned about how it was done was the Disney film- "The Black Hole" Truly incredible how they did the black hole effect and the visuals are just breath taking. Even to this day, much like Star Wars, it really is a brilliant movie with many stunning visual effects and scenes. I may just sub if you take a look at it. :P

I'd also love to give Sky Captain and the world of tomorrow an honorable mention, because it's a tremendous tribute to 'ye olde time' special effects and prop making.
